english:
  title: Record of the New Construction of the Junbang Official Hall
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the tenth month of winter in the year Gyeha of Hongwu, Eagle-Rising Guard Pae Gu came bearing words from his superior, the Privy Counselor Choe Gong, saying: "We humbly trouble you, Master, to compose a record of our junbang renovation." He then presented the construction ledger.

    The great hall stood three bays wide, the western chamber three bays, the tower storehouse three bays, the southern corridor nine bays, and one gateway. All adorned with cinnabar and vermillion. Walls encircled the perimeter. Truly a great undertaking. Timber was purchased at fair price; what was lacking, the Grand Commander Choe, the Minister of State, supplied—two hundred fifty bolts of silk from the patrol army stores. Officers were dispatched to oversee the work, dividing the soldiers into teams. The craftsmen, those at home in their trades, eagerly hired themselves out. Carts were rented to haul materials. Officials were sent to direct the labor. Work began on the twenty-fourth day of the fifth month and concluded on the last day of the ninth month.

    I said: "How admirably managed! Here was a public project, yet the common people knew nothing of it. When those above undertake something, those below rally to support it—such harmony is rarely heard in these times." The directing officers, I learned, were: the Great Guard Choe Sung-ka, and when he neared completion, the court assigned Yom Chi-jung to take his place. Yet from beginning to end, only Pae Jun truly oversaw the work. Beneath him served the Commandants Choe Yeu and Kim Ul-jung; the Adjutant Pae Chon-sok; the Unranked Officer Yun Young-yol; and further down, the Chief Inspector Won Ul-bu, the Scribe Lee Im-bal, and the Clerical Assistant Chong Kyu-bu. Such was the undertaking, directed by the junbang superior. From the highest rank down to the lowest clerk, all were enrolled and recorded in writing. Is this not glory?

    I reflect that both the civil and military serve the nation's needs—like the two arms of a body, like the two wheels of a carriage. Neither can be neglected. Yet times vary between order and chaos, and uses must shift between priority and secondary importance. In these troubled days, we civilians may well retreat to the background. The military officers are the nation's ramparts and talons, the executors of the state's will—this much is clear. Choe Gong is renowned for his loyalty and virtue; the throne knows him well. He participates in matters of state secrets, yet remains humble and respectful. Those in court all revere and admire him. That his officers and soldiers follow willingly is only natural. Thus, should urgent crisis arise, we may trust they will surge forth courageously. How much more so for this modest construction project?

    At fifteen, I received the rank of Adjutant through my father's favor, without taking the civil service examination—thus I too am an officer of the Eagle-Rising Guard. When the junbang superior requested my brush, how could I refuse? Moreover, military officials prize simplicity. Therefore I have merely recorded the facts plainly, without elaborate words. The junbang superior presides over the western division, the most honored of the eight supreme generals. For this reason, the great ministers of both offices often hold his position concurrently.
  footnotes:
    - The 'junbang' (중방, 重房) was an important administrative division within the Goryeo and early Joseon military bureaucracy, composed of military officials.
    - Choe Young (최영, 崔瑩), referenced here as 'Grand Commander Choe the Minister of State,' was one of the most powerful military figures in early Joseon, known for his role in stabilizing the dynasty.
    - The eight supreme generals (상장군, 上將軍) represented the highest military ranks in the early Joseon military hierarchy.
